1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,945
Mr. Activationist plans a vacation.

2
00:00:04,975 --> 00:00:05,984
He takes it.

3
00:00:06,255 --> 00:00:12,144
Mr. Passivationist plans a vacation, but he postpones it until next year.

4
00:00:12,415 --> 00:00:16,065
Mr. A decides he should attend church regularly.

5
00:00:16,255 --> 00:00:17,105
He does.

6
00:00:17,294 --> 00:00:21,105
Mr. P thinks it's a good idea to go to church regularly,

7
00:00:21,135 --> 00:00:25,665
too, but he finds ways to postpone acquiring this new habit.

8
00:00:26,174 --> 00:00:32,305
Mr. A feels that he should drop a note to someone he knows to congratulate him on some achievement.

9
00:00:32,334 --> 00:00:33,665
He writes the note.

10
00:00:34,014 --> 00:00:39,745
Under the same circumstances, Mr. P finds a good reason to put off writing the note,

11
00:00:39,774 --> 00:00:41,505
and it never gets written.

12
00:00:42,415 --> 00:00:45,105
The difference shows up in big things, too.

13
00:00:45,373 --> 00:00:48,225
Mr. A wants to go into business for himself.

14
00:00:48,255 --> 00:00:49,185
He does.

15
00:00:49,535 --> 00:00:58,385
Mr. P also wants to go into business for himself, but he discovers just in the nick of time a good reason why he had better not.

16
00:00:58,734 --> 00:01:03,185
Mr. A, age forty, decides he wants to take up a new line of work.

17
00:01:03,294 --> 00:01:04,225
He does.

18
00:01:04,494 --> 00:01:10,704
The same idea occurs to Mr. P, but he debates himself out of doing anything about it.

19
00:01:11,374 --> 00:01:18,465
The difference between Messer's activationist and passivationist shows through in all forms of behavior.

20
00:01:18,894 --> 00:01:25,105
Mr. A gets the things done he wants done, and as byproducts he gains confidence,

21
00:01:25,135 --> 00:01:29,505
a feeling of inner security, self-reliance, and more income.

22
00:01:30,174 --> 00:01:34,945
Mr. P doesn't get the things done he wants done because he won't act.

23
00:01:35,054 --> 00:01:42,225
As byproducts, he loses confidence in himself, destroys his self-reliance, lives in mediocrity.

24
00:01:42,894 --> 00:01:45,423
Mr. Activationist does.

25
00:01:45,614 --> 00:01:49,744
Mr. Passivationist is going to do, but doesn't.

26
00:01:50,415 --> 00:01:52,864
Everyone wants to be an Activationist.

27
00:01:52,975 --> 00:01:55,504
So, let's get the action habit.

28
00:01:56,174 --> 00:02:06,064
A lot of Passivationists got that way because they insisted on waiting until everything was 100% favorable before they took action.

29
00:02:06,415 --> 00:02:15,025
Perfection is highly desirable, but nothing man-made or man-designed is or can be absolutely perfect.

30
00:02:15,215 --> 00:02:19,744
So to wait for the perfect set of conditions is to wait forever.

31
00:02:21,134 --> 00:02:29,105
Here are three case histories that show how three persons reacted to conditions.

